deck_excerpt: Facedown your enemies, use Dancing-leaves make them a ninja, use Ninja Tistina to OTK your opponent.
deck_description:
Facedown your enemies, use Dancing-leaves make them a ninja, use Ninja Tistina to OTK your opponent. 

Simple Facedown Sample
your opponent has monsters on the field
1 summon "Sentinel of the Tistina"
2 set "Ninjitsu-Art Notebook"
3 activate "Sentinel of the Tistina" destroying the facedown "Ninjitsu-Art Notebook" , then add "Demigod of the Tistina"
4 activate 2nd effect of "Ninjitsu-Art Notebook" to flip-facedown one of your enemies monsters.
5 with "Demigod of the Tistina" on hand use its effect to special summon, then add "Breath of the Tistina"
6 place and activate "Breath of the Tistina" since you have  "Demigod of the Tistina" you can instead facedown one of your opponents monster's if they have another faceup on the field, then you can add another "Tistina" card.

If you opponent rely to much on the Graveyard Loop, you need to side.

This is a super cool deck archetype! It is one I would see a lot while playing Duel Links. I think this is an obvious reference to the Ishtar family and their roles of watching over the tomb of the Pharoah along with some of the Millennium Items. It's always great to see something from the animes turned into physical game. Anyways, enjoy the deck!

deck_excerpt: My attempt at a decent Goblin Biker deck
deck_description:
So what is the Goblin Biker Archetype

The Goblin Bikers are a new archetype coming in Phantom Nightmare who focuses on Level/Rank 3 monster

Some notable main deck monster are Dugg the Charger who can summon himself from the hand by detaching a XYZ material from ANY monster on the field and then on summon it lets you add an archetypal spell/trap,

Mean Merciless who on summon can special another goblin from hand and can revive itself from the the grave by detatching an XYZ material,

Then we have the only 2 ekstra deck monster the rank 3 Big-Head Gabonga on summon he lets you add any goblin card from the deck and whenere an XYZ material is detached he can attatch a face up monster to him as material, 

the rank 6? Goblins' Crazy Beast who can detatch 2 materials from the field to attach a spell/trap to it, protect a goblin from destruction by detatching an XYZ material from itself and can revive itself from the grave while also attatching a goblin to it. 

But wait rank 6 isnt this an archetype of level 3s how does it make a rank 6, thats where the spells come lets start with the continuous spell Goblin Biker Grand Bash which gives all goblins a 300 atk bosst for every goblin on the field, gives you an extra normal summon for a goblin and the most interestting effect by targeting to goblins make one of them the level of the other or make the levels the combined total of the two goblins. 

and now the last spell in the deck Goblin Biker Grand Entrance letting you add a goblin from the deck, then after you add a goblin letting you special a goblin by detatching an XYZ material and by banshing itself from the grave lets you detach an XYZ material and then adding a goblin from the grave to the hand

Thats the way to long overwiev of the archetypes best cards, so now what are the decs strengths and weaknesses

lets start with the decks strengths 1. The decks biggest strenght is its consistency, with how many 1 card combos and free extenders the deck has makes it so it doesnt brick very often and even if it does there still a high chance that you'll still get some form of interruption up. 2. The decks flexibility makes it so it can be played in alot of differnt ways ways adding in a gold pride engine to use alongside the P.u.n.k cards and with Grand Bash lets the deck use almost any XYZ monster as long as you play other goblin cards for example by using a card like goblin zombie you gain acces to both rank 4 and 7 XYZ monster while  goblin zombie also has the abillity to search any of Goblin Riders when its sent from the field to the grave.

Now for the decks weaknesses 1. the deck can have a pretty hard time going 2nd against a lot of the stronger deck even though the the deck can usally play through 1 or 2 distruptions going 2nd but with some hands it can struggle. 2. this deck is another basic combo deck that just looses hard to droll and nibiru but with nib its still possible to get gossip shadow out before they can activate it but with droll if you dont open called by it can just end your turn a lot of the time.

now for as the last thing i'll go over 2 1 card combosthe first is for Terrortop and Ze Amin and 1 for Tour Guide, even though they end on the same board the Tour Guide one still uses a few less resources and gives you more to work with.

One Card Ze Amin replay https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=851484-57134861

if you openend Terrortop or Ze amin, make Gabonga add Dugg, Dugg effect to special itself, Dugg effect to add Grand Entrance, use the 1st effect of Grand Entrance to add Mean Merciless and the 2nd to special it, overlay Dugg and mean into Alucard then overlay it into Angel of mischief, Angel effect detaching Alucard  to add ghostrick shot, shot effect to revive Alucard once again overlay Alucard into Angel, both Angels overlay to make F0 into UFD, use Grand Entrance 3rd effect to detach a xyz material and add Dugg back to hand the use Means grave effect to revive itself by detaching a xyz materiel and on summon special Dugg overlay them for Armor Torpedo then activating its effect to draw 2 then overlaying for Armor Fortress then Fortress effect to add Full Armored XYZ.

the Tour Guide version of this combo is a little bit different

One Card Tour Guide Replay https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=851484-57134739

Summon Tour Guide, Tour Guide effect summon Rhino Warrior, overlay for Gabonga add Dugg, Dugg effect detaching Rhino Warrior, CL1 Dugg CL2 Rhino Warrior, Rhino Warrior dumps Mean merciless, Dugg adds Grand Entrance, Grand Enctrance adds and specials Clatter Sploder, Clatter effect to summon Mean from grave overlay Clatter and mean for alucard to do the UFD line, then use Means grave effect to summon itself, use it and Dugg to over lay into Armor torpede and do the Full armor line

deck_description: Yay no special summons
Deck anime blues angel
Just a Z-arc deck

Be warned, this deck is not looking for putting up negates, it merely puts up a big wall other decks have to try to get over. It can however be modified to make negates such as through Firewall.

The main field you want to end with is wiccid in one of the extra monster zones with invalid dolmen directly underneath and accelerator to the right of dolmen. This creates a lock that makes your monsters unaffected by other monster effects, your monsters cant be destroyed by card effects and your opponent must battle dolmen who with the help of accelerator can get to 4800 attack. Accelerator can be switch out for honeybot, it just depends on how many monsters you can bring out.

When going first I suggest just putting in as many cyberse monsters who can special summon themselves to prevent a much damage from nibiru. If your opponent is playing nibiru every game, sub in the firewall package or better cyberse link monsters to end in a substantially sized Arrival Cyberse (its better than nothing). 

When going second, I suggest subbing in dark ruler, droll and evenly (anything to prevent interuptions). When subbing I take out 1x Reborn, 1x f.a.ighting spirit, 2x parallel exceed, 2x upstart goblin, 1x meet you and 1x mathmech addition.

I wanted to make a mostly pure @ignister deck, it is by no means perfect but it will definitely give some decks a challenge. It is pretty fun to use in a semi competitive setting. If you have any ideas to make this deck better please comment.

deck_description:
And here is the Sea Serpent-flavored White Fish deck I promised you. I replaced most of the ice themes with deeper waters (Ran Aegirine is still a free Gymir). Honestly, this is probably the weaker and less consistent version of the two, but I love and am equally committed to all of these engines. I even sided a tiny Mermail package. I didn't want the deck to go over 40 since you want to see Diva more than anything, but maybe you could take out one Heavy Infantry and something else. The idea on that is to add Abyssteus to hand with Abyssalacia so you don't have to waste Abyssdine's summon on your opponent's turn. But I digress.

Summoning Guitar Gurnards Duonigis, hands-down the coolest Sea Serpent, with Diva gets you level 7 or 8 synchros. With all your free summons, it just snowballs from there. Atlanteans do Atlantean things to hand-loop; DS Minstrel is an anti-handtrap; and the other Deep Seas are extenders when discarded/ss'd. Chengying might be a better pick than Bihamut, who just starts with higher attack. I wanted a big beatstick to contend with "unaffected" monsters. Duonigis does give an attack buff from the gy.

Sadly, we are only getting 1 Toad off of Bahamut Shark with this deck. The only level 2 Aqua that would fit with this deck is Swap Frog, and trying to field 2 of him is just too hard. Plus I don't wanna pay his tax when I could still run Ran instead. Boy I'm looking forward to these water cards. I hope they're not expensive.

Greetings! Are you a fan of Yata-Lock and Destiny Board? If you like both, this deck is for you. Also, compared to my previous Destiny Board setups I did, this one was easy to execute because the chance of hitting bricks are reduced. Alright, let's get started!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Draw until you find these combo pieces: Yata + Droll + Miracle Locus + Disturbance Strategy + Destiny Board. Meanwhile, bring forth Apollousa + Baronne. Then, set Disturbance + Miracle + Destiny and end your turn but not before changing the button at the lower right corner of the screen to "ON". You don't want to miss anything happening, do you?

  • As seen in the video, I was about to discard my key pieces. Therefore, shuffle other letters with Saryuja to not risk them being sent to GY. If you are really concerned, you can add 1 x Infinite Cards as a workaround for discard issue, seen in "Side Deck". When you are about to place last letter, you can destroy "Infinite Cards" with Baronne anyways, so backrow space isn't an issue.
  • Similar to Dugares which can draw cards and skip your next Draw Phase to not deck-out, Daigusto can refill your Main Deck. As a mini "Pot of Avarice" with XYZ body, feel free to replace Dugares with Daigusto, if you wish. You can check Daigusto in "Side Deck".
  • "Sword of Deep-Seated" was added to solve issues of deck-out. As you place letters with "Destiny Board", it will be inevitable you draw cards, leading into deck-out. By applying Deep-Seated to Yata, when you hit End Phase, Deep-Seated will be automatically destroyed after Yata has returned to your hand. As its ability, Deep-Seated will be placed on top of your Main Deck...
    • Sabres can achieve the similar thing by shuffling one of your cards from your hand on top of your Main Deck to Special Summon itself. To make it a loop, you have to destroy Sabres with Baronne. You can check Sabres in "Side Deck".

2) During your opponent's Standby Phase, activate Miracle to let your opponent draw a card. Then, activate Disturbance and chain into Droll. What will happen is Droll denies for either side to add any card to their hand. Therefore, by shuffling your opponent's hand into deck with Disturbance, they won't be able to draw/add any card afterwards, all thanks to Droll.

3) Your opponent has nothing to do but pass the turn back to you. However, before that, activate "Destiny Board" if you haven't already at End Phase of your opponent and start placing letters. When it's your turn, destroy "Chicken Game" if present and Normal Summon Yata-Garasu. Attack the opponent with Yata, which denies your opponent from drawing any card.

4) Your opponent will be stuck forever. So, they can either surrender or wait for animation of "Destiny Board", as long as you repeat what was explained in #3. Either way, you win the duel!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Destiny Board" can be found within "The Trap in the Wicked Castle" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Baronne de Fleur" can be found within "The Noble Knights of Crimson Flowers" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Mannadium Trisukta" can be found within "Indomitable Pride" Timed Pack to save 30 SR! Don't miss out before it's too late!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 510 SR and 90 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Red Dragon now has 15 1-card starters thanks to Maze of Millennia!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
This is my personal Red Dragon Archfiend deck for Locals, but updated for the TCG 2024 metagame! 
 
With Maze of Millennia, Red Dragon Archfiend obtains three additional 1 card starters to initiate full combo which is Earthbound Prisoner Stone Sweeper (total of 15 1-card starters)! The card can be discarded to search for any level 3 or lower fiend tuner. Of course in the Red Dragon Archfiend strategy, that would obtain us Soul Resonator or any other missing combo piece. 
 
With this added bit of consistency with an incredible 15 one-card starters (thanks fo the x3 Stone Sweeper from MZMI), additional staples can be added into the deck. The staples in this iteration of the deck is built around Crossout Designator and its targets since this strategy is vulnerable to handtraps. This grants us a grand total of 11 handtraps and 4 anti-handtrap cards (Called By + 3 Crossouts). 
 
The Side Deck is specialized to counter the 2024 January meta, especially with the Soul Releases. When siding out, simply switch in the most relevant staples with other staples already in the deck (for ex,. swap out your Crossouts for Droplets when forced to go second). 
 
Best thing of all, this deck doesn't require the RIDICULOUSLY expensive cards that dominate the meta this format while being competitive! No need to bust your wallet for Bonfire, WANTED: Seeker of Sinful Spoils and S:P Little Knight!
 
If you want a more detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, please check out my earlier article on Red Dragon Archfiend. 
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_name: Intro to Link Summoning Featuring Dinowrestlers
deck_description:
Intro to Link Summoning and Link Climbing

Feat. Dinosaurs/ Dinowrestlers

1200+ word article.

 

(In April 2023, I burnt out from being a teacher and applied to be a YGOPROdeck writer for some scratch cash for hobby writing. I sent a few articles and remember getting good feedback but then got ghosted. It didn't matter much anyways because even if I had gotten hired, my new job overwhelmed me to have little time to play YuGiOh or keep up with product)

I found this lesson article written hastily in a week for that position on my pc and decided to upload it here. 

 

Introduction

Link Monsters are some of the most versatile Extra Deck monsters in the YuGiOh trading card game, capable of being summoned using generic material. Link monsters can also add more strategy to a player’s extra deck and helping a player get out of a situation with no other meaningful plays. With their inclusion, players are also encouraged to consider which zones to place monsters, spells, and traps.

However, Link Monsters are arguably trickier to summon in contrast with their previous Extra Deck monster types: Fusions, Synchros, and XYZ with regards to Link Zones and Link Ratings. With the latest Wild Survivor Set bringing Dinosaurs back to the forefront, and seeing many players at my locals get into the game with the Traptrix structure deck, I wanted to write an introduction on how to Link Summon, using the Dinosaur archetype as an example and to see how the Dinosaur archetype link climbs with the new card support!

 

Link Summoning Basics

Link Summoning is most often performed by using Monsters a player controls as Link Material for a Link Monster. During their Main Phase, if the game state is open, the turn player can Link Summon a Link Monster from their Extra Deck by sending face-up monsters they control that correspond to the Link Monster’s summoning requirements equal Link Monster’s Link Rating to the Graveyard as Link Materials. The Link Monster is Summoned in either an Extra Monster Zone or a Main Monster Zone that a Link Monster on the field points to in face-up Attack Position.

Link Ratings are defined by the number on the Bottom Right, in the place where most monsters have a defense point number. The Link Rating is formed by the addition of Link Monster ratings and non-link Monsters used for the summon. For instance, the Link Monster Saryuja Skull Dread has a Link rating of 4 and has the Link Material requirement of “2+ monsters with different names”.  So, you could use a 4 monsters, a Link 3 and any other monster, two Link 2’s, etc. Another way to think of this is a non-link monster can be thought of as a Link 1 material.

Link Monsters are unique in that they are monsters that have no defense and can only be in face-up Attack Position, a condition that no other monster type has. Thus, cards that force monsters to be in defense position such as Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir or Scareclaw Tri-Heart have no effect on Link Monsters.

 

Link Arrows

 

Link Arrows are important as they give positions for which other Link Monsters can be summoned. However, more importantly, Link Monster often have abilities that correspond to the place where their arrows point.

Link Monsters are Summoned in either an Extra Monster Zone or a Main Monster Zone that a Link Monster on the field points to in face-up Attack Position. A player can only use one Extra Monster Zone. However, a player can claim both extra monster zones if their link monsters point to both monster zones, which is a very impressive feat. Unlike other extra deck monster types, which are free to be placed anywhere on your board, Link Monsters must be summoned to a zone a Link Monster Points to, otherwise they must be in the extra monster zones. As such, a player must be careful which zones they summon to. For instance, if a player fusion summoned a monster with a spell and placed that monster in the extra monster zone, and had no other link monsters, that player cannot link summon unless they use that fusion summoned monster as material.

Link Arrows are important because many Link Monster have special varying based on their Link Arrows. For instance, the Link 3 monster card Transcendonsarus Exaraptor has Link Arrows Pointing Up, Left, and Right. Its ability states that if a face-up Dinosaur monster(s) this points to is destroyed by battle or sent to the GY: You can draw one card. So, in the case of a dinosaur deck, a player could be encouraged to use the cards Lost World or Dogoroan, the Mad Flame Kaiju to summon a dinosaur in a zone that will point on the Link 3 monster will point to and destroy it later.

As a bit of trivia, upon release, players were not allowed to summon any Extra Deck monsters outside the two Extra Monster Zones unless linked. As such, link summoning on release was wedged into the game, and many players disliked the mechanic. Decks had to shoehorn link summoning into their deck. Alternatively, many tournament players used decks that did not utilize the extra deck at all such as Monarchs or True Dracos or used decks that banished Extra Deck monster such as True King Dinos.

 

Link Archetypes/ Strategies

Link Monsters are arguably the most versatile extra deck monster, requiring none of the specific monster levels that Synchros and XYZ require nor the Specific monsters that Fusions require. In addition, Link Monster have a host of generic support such as Knightmares, which can be used for spot removal, or Charmers. In addition, with boss monsters such as Appaloosa Bow of the Goddess and Accesscode Talkers, Link monsters are great for many decks that can produce many creatures in one turn. In addition, the classic sideboard card Dimensional Barrier does not prevent Link Monsters from being summoned from the extra deck and provides an alternate series of deck types against these duels. Duelists are encouraged to experiment with extra deck archetypes.

Several Archetypes revolve around Link Summoning multiple times to climb to more and more powerful monster. As such, the term Link Climbing became slang for using another Link Monster as material. Some classic decks include Salamgreats, Sky Strikers, @Ignister. Dinosaurs have their own specific archetype: Dinowrestlers, but most meta Dino decks splash generic Link Support for their strategy. As such, Duelists are encouraged to experiment with several rations of their monsters alongside other extra deck archetypes.

For this example, many Dinosaur Decks run many generic and niche Link cards to support this strategy. Link monsters are also great for extending plays or setting up future players. For instance, Dinosaur decks often use card Animadorned Archosaur to search for Double Evolution Pill. In order to achieve the requirements of a non-dinosaur monster for Pill, a player can link away Animadorned Archosaur with Linkuriboh, a Link 1 that can stall the game but also achieve the second monster necessary for pill. 

As a general guide, Link Decks would be advised to count their summons up to 4 in case of a Nibiru hand trap, which can be catastrophic against a Link Deck. If a player summons 5 or more monsters during their turn, Nibiru can be activated to tribute all monsters on the field. Against Link monster, this will end with each Link Monsters being tributed for 0 def. As such, players are advised to stop at 4 or end with a monster negate such as Apolloussa, Bow of the Goddess.

I hope this guide helped introduce you to the Link Summoning. While I had originally wanted to describe Link Monsters in Dinosaur decks, I was surprised to discover their rich and jaded history. I started the game a little confused with Link Monsters and Link scales, so I hope this guide makes players less confused and more intrigued. Today, I always manage to splash a few link monsters into most of my decks with their sheer versatility. I’m always excited to see more Link monsters being released into the game!

BO1 build. Running the D/D/D/D Boss for possible in-engine floodgate boardwipes from hand. (Buster Lock, Bagooska, Skill Drain, etc.) This deck can run basic 1 card combo's, however requires lots of practice and experimentation to make full use of the 2 and 3 card combos the deck offers. Attached is a link to the D/D/D starter combo guide: https://www.masterduelmeta.com/articles/guides/d-d-d-combo-guide-yusodus

This deck is not running D/D/D Oracle so certain combo lines from the combo guide are limited due to an emphasis on board breaking/interruption with Super Polymerization. The deck is fairly consistent, however on brick hands you can set Super Poly and pass with Maxx C, to hopefully fuse into Garura or Mudragon using your opponent's board. You can fuse into Garura to out a Nibiru and Nibiru token as well with Super Poly. I would recommend playtesting this deck on EDO Pro or YGO Omega, however it's fairly cheap in Master Duel compared to newer Meta decks. D/D/D is a very fun deck to learn, as well as experiment with. You can run the Zeus, Vice King Build. Kali Yuga Lock build with Wonder Xyz, as well as Doom King build. 

Example Combo:

1 Card Kepler to summon D/D/D Duo-Dawn King Kali Yuga: Normal Summon Kepler - Add Dark Contract With the Gate - Activate Gate's effect - Add D/D Gryphon from deck to hand. - Special Summon D/D Gryphon using Gryphon's effect - Link into D/D/D Abyss King Gilgamesh - Place Scales D/D Orthros, D/D Savant Thomas - Activate D/D Savant Thomas's pendulum effect to add Kepler from face up extra deck to hand - Activate D/D Orthros pendulum effect to pop D/D Savant Thomas and Dark Contract with the Gate - Place Kepler in Scales - Pendulum Summon D/D Savant Thomas and D/D Gryphon - Activate D/D Savant Thomas's field effect to summon D/D/D Oblivion King Abyss Ragnarok from deck - Xyz Summon D/D/D Duo-Dawn King Kali Yuga using D/D Savant Thomas, and D/D/D Oblivion King Abyss Ragnarok. 

Enjoy, and have fun experimenting, as D/D/D has a ton of great combos.

deck_excerpt: Yugi Muto's deck updated. Trying to bring the best out of his character deck whilst keeping it in the DM era.
deck_description:
Dark Magic Games, Yugi Muto's deck updated. Trying to bring the best out of his character deck whilst keeping it in the DM era so no Synchro, Xyz, Pendulum or Link monsters.

Let me know if you would do anything different.

One of the funniest deck I've ever played, not a meta deck but definitely not a bad deck ! Try it, give it a chance, you might be surprised by how powerful it can be !

Note that this deck is NOT a Runick variation but a Generaider one. Runick is only here to support the Generaider archetype with more interruptions, consistency and the recent add of Sleipnir in DUNE gives the deck free level 9 bodies.

 

MONSTERS :

Vala : Main starter of your combos. Excellent in grind game since you can make it come back from graveyard every turn, just make sure to always use her as XYZ Material before detaching it, so she won't get banished.

Harr : Godlike card. Omni negate by tributing 2 Generaiders + makes your opponent send a Monster to graveyard if he adds a card from main to hand. This effect can be forced by Jormungandr.

Mardel : Makes you search anything you need, especially Boss Stage.

Hela : Makes you bring back your other Generaiders from graveyard if already used + a Zombie Type for Monstrosity.

Utgarda : Banish 1, not used very often but we need some other names in the deck. Can be switched for Nagflar for more protection (especially for the Field) and to have a Fire Attribute and Beast-Warrior target for Monstrosity

Loptr : One of the 2 normal summon of the deck. Can tribute himself as cost to play around Veiler or Imperm to special summon any other Generaider like Mardel to search for the Field. Boosting everybody and can tribute Generaider Tokens during opponent's turn to gain more bodies and control

 

Diviner : One card combo Baronne de Fleur. Can foolish a Vala to start combos if opening Trias.

Trias Hierarchia : Level 9. Part of the Baronne combo. Can be Special Summoned during opponent's turn by tributing Tokens to destroy/draw. You can tribute Vala or Hughin to dodge Veiler/Imperm or targetting effects. (ONLY IN MAIN PHASE)

D.D. Sprite : Just a Level 1 Tuner Special Summoned by Diviner for the Baronne Play.

 

SPELLS :

RUNICK PACKAGE : Very classic ratios. Gives you more interruptions, ways to draw you starting pieces and free bodies with lvl 9 Sleipnirs. Only 1 Fountain because you want Boss Stage on the field and not Fountain.

Boss Stage : Core of the deck, you can't play without it and is an insane card. Special Summons a Generaider + Tokens during opponent's turn (especially during Draw Phase). You can Summon Harr for a free Omni-negate or bring him from GY with Hela or Vala. (just be sure to tribute a Token with Hela's effect) Terraforming makes 4 copies of Boss Stage if not more since you can search it with a Loptr/Mardel.

World Legacy Monstrosity : Busted card. Makes you Special Summon 1 Level 9 from hand OR 2 Level 9 from deck with different Attributes and Types than the targeted Boss. Give you access to free XYZ.

 

EXTRA DECK :

 

Laevatein : Best Extra deck card ever printed. Tribute itself as cost, making it naturally playing around any HT or targeting effect (except for Called By), to Special Summon Jormungandr and "Super Polymerisation" opponent's Field + Graveyard. Makes you play around Towers and even Bagooska. Absolutely broken, summon it on every board you make if possible.

Jormungandr : Might feel not that powerful but can have very big stats very fast and makes you trigger a lot of interesting effects since it makes your Opponent draw as Quick Effect : 

- You can Droll & Lock Bird your opponent in Standby before he can search anything.

- Triggers Harr effect to make your opponent discard a monster.

- Makes you Special Summon a Generaider during your turn with Boss Stage.

 

Enterblathnir : All of his effects banishes and are not targeting. Very versatile depending on the situation, especially the ban from hand, very powerful. Not "Hard Once per Turn" so you can banish two cards from opponent's hand then XYZ into Number F0.

Number F0 : You might want to get rid of some of your other XYZ once their effects are used, so you can keep up with some more control with those boys.

Ty-Phon : Go second option in case you bricked or the opponent has too many interruptions.

Baronne de Fleur : Generic Synchro 10 made with Diviner. Baronne should be your 4th summon when doing the Diviner play, plays around Nibiru.

S:P Little Knight : No surprise, very strong card. Easily made with a Runick Fusion and another body to banish an opponent card.

Hughin : Can't really play Runick without her ! Search Foutain and prevent your cards from destruction, can be useful to protect Boss Stage.

Geri : If you need to get the Foutain back from GY and puts pressure during battle.

Sleipnir : Best Runick card ever !! Level 9 so enables a lot of combo and is a free body to use for XYZ plays. Has a very cool effect too in case you need to get rid of something to start your combos.

 

 

BARONNE DE FLEUR COMBO :

- Normal Summon Diviner, effect => Foolish Trias (1st Summon)

- Trias Effect in grave ,Tribute Diviner => Special Summon Trias from graveyard (2nd Summon)

- Diviner effect when tributed => Special Summon D.D. Sprite from deck (3rd Summon)

- Synchro Summon Baronne de Fleur (4th Summon)
Have fun with this deck. It's my attempt at Rokkets

deck_excerpt: Jackpot 7 FTK ft. Primal Seed + Morphing Jar #2
deck_description:
Hey, how you doing? A while ago, I won with Jackpot 7 by utilizing Morphing Jar #2. However, there was a chance you could fail. This time, as long as you have time to establish the setup needed, you can absolutely win with Jackpot 7 alongside MJ2 by disregarding any margin of error. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Plant at least one flower to opposing side with "Black Garden" and play "Double Summon". Double will be used for putting MJ2 as Set.

2) When you have 4 cards in your Main Deck, Link Summon Saryuja and activate it. There, you draw all remaining cards and shuffle back three, which has to be "Jackpot 7".

3) Special Summon Kuriboh with Saryuja and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Then, place MJ2 as Set.

4) If you have Main Deck monsters on the battlefield, other than Chaos + Kuriboh + MJ2, get rid of them by passing to opposing side with "Mystic Box" while eradicating the flowers. When you have only these three, only pass MJ2 to your opponent with "Mystic Box" for one last time.

5) When you have "Monster Reborn" + "Monster Reincarnation" in your hand, activate "Book of Taiyou" on MJ2 to open it. While MJ2 triggers, you will shuffle back Chaos + Kuriboh + MJ2 to your Main Deck and in the end, MJ2 will be placed as face-down while Chaos + Kuriboh were sent to GY.

6) Besides the events happening in #5, there is a chance you can hit all three Jackpot 7 cards. Since MJ2 was placed to your opponent's side, the effects coming from MJ2 were considered to be done by your opponent. Therefore, by milling all three Jackpot 7 cards, you win the duel. Even if you own MJ2, this fact won't change...

  • However, the excavate effect of MJ2 isn't guaranteed to find Jackpot 7 cards since you shuffle your Main Deck. If you miss any one of Jackpot 7 cards, that means you have to repeat same setup done in #4 + #5.
  • In order to do so, first play "Monster Reborn" and target on Kuriboh. Reason is that, in case you didn't realize already, "Winged Kuriboh LV9" sends any activated Spell cards into BZ instead of GY. Since "Primal Seed" can only fetch cards from BZ, I think you see the pattern now.
  • With Kuriboh present, you can play "Monster Reincarnation" to add Chaos Emperor from your GY back to your hand. Return from BZ to GY, 1 x LIGHT + 1 x DARK monster, with "Burial from a Different Dimension" and Special Summon Chaos Emperor via its ability. Your "Primal Seed" loop is completely restructured.
  • While Special Summoning monsters, "Black Garden" is going to plant flowers to opposing side. Give MJ2 to the opponent with "Mystic Box" and fetch all combo pieces with "Primal Seed" loop, which are Mystic Box + Monster Reincarnation + Monster Reborn + Different Dimension + Book of Taiyou. Finally, play "Book of Taiyou" on MJ2.

7) Repeat what was explained in #6 until you have milled all three Jackpot 7 cards with MJ2 to win the duel!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" + "Jackpot 7" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 150 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 690 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!
Ritual beast

deck_excerpt: TSX1 Flame Swordsman Infernoble deck list
deck_description: TSX1 Flame Swordsman Infernoble deck list

Introducing Yugioh's incredible "Darklord" deck, also known as "Fallen Angel". This deck is simply brilliant, as it represents the 9 Deadly Sins, and not just the traditional 7, as many think. The Catholic Church has tried to hide two of these sins, but we will not let this go unnoticed.

Let's start with Asmodeus, the sin of Lust, represented by the card "Darklord Asmodeus". This card is as powerful as it is tempting. The next sin is Gluttony, represented by Beelzebub and the card "Darklord Tezcatlipoca". Mammon represents Greed with the card "Darklord Desire" and Belphegor personifies Sloth through the card "Darklord Nergal". Azazel that represents Wrath is actually the card "Darklord Nasten" and a Daemon (sin Envy) that represents the card "Darklord Amdusc". We cannot forget the powerful Lucifer, Pride himself, who manifests himself in the card "Darklord Morningstar".

deck_excerpt: An ABC deck intended to contend with the meta utilizing the Revolution Synchron and Therion packages.
deck_description:
In essence, you're intended to, in the most optimal circumstances, end on:

ABC Dragon Buster + Therion King Regulus + Crystal Wing Sychro Dragon + I:P Masquerena + S:P Little Knight 

I'd usually like to prefer to have another open slot to tag out ABC Dragon Buster at any instance but S:P Little Knight is a decent enough protector both when your ending your first-turn after building your board and during your opponent's next turn. Furthermore, the ability of cards like S:P Little Knight and Therion King Regulus to remove themselves from the field after doing their job leaves you open to being able to tag out ABC Dragon Buster thereafter. 

I intend to experiment with this further. It certainly invites consistency to ABC that the deck lacked last I played the game to the point I'm considering ditching the Pots of Prosperity or getting by with but a single Union Driver since the danger of your entire gamestrategy falling to hell as a result of dead drawing your lone copy isn't that much of an issue anymore. Perhaps the side and extra decks needs more work, as well. I imagine most people would tell me to drop Borrelsword but I like having that additional boss monster so as to have more options to go into during a battle of attrition with battles of attrition being what ABC - with its ability to recycle and abuse resources - excels at. 

All in all, I'm happy to hear suggestions.

This 60-card variant of Branded somewhat alleviates Branded's weakness to ash (used by 90% of decks in Masterduel right now) by giving the pilot so much gas and plays to work with so that you can play through devastating handtraps and eventually out-resource your opponent! This "gas" variant of Branded can keep playing, even though Branded Fusion is negated!
 
Able to play through commonly used turn-stopping cards like Dimension Shifter, Maxx "C," Nibiru, and Droll Branded is a top pick for Masterduel's meta right now!
 
It's incredible that Branded is still Masterduel's strongest deck (according to tournament and ladder results) despite all the hits to the strategy and Branded Fusion limited to 1!

If you're looking for the perfect deck to pilot that can slice through those annoying omni-negate decks, while strong and consistent enough to create it's own powerful boards, Branded Fusion is the deck for you! Reach Masters 1 on ladder with the strongest fusion deck on Masterduel, Branded Despia!

Chances are if you're reading this, you've been piloting Branded for a couple years now (wow time flies fast) and you don't need a combo guide for the deck. However, if you wanna read up an article I made, feel free to check out my guide!

deck_excerpt: Nightingale FTK ft. Fusion Gate + Starving Venom + Primal Seed
deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, we will FTK our opponent with "Starving Venom Fusion Dragon" thanks to "Independent Nightingale". With Banisher and Fusion Gate around, you can cycle mats needed with "Primal Seed", making it a complete loop. Let's go!

 

 

Gameplan

1) First, place a plant to your opponent's field with "Black Garden". Next, bring out Swallow and play "Cattle Call" to replace it with Nightingale. Then, give Nightingale to opposing side by replacing the flower with "Mystic Box".

2) After you have Link Summoned Saryuja, Special Summon Banisher with Saryuja. Then, Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop.

3) Place "Fusion Gate" and raise the level of Nightingale to 5, which is needed to copycat Nightingale with Starving. Then, Special Summon Jester with its ability to Link Summon Barber by using Saryuja + Jester as materials.

4) Since the Special Summon ability of Jester isn't hard-once per turn, you can repeat it as many times as you like. Fetch Jester from BZ with "Primal Seed" and Special Summon it. Then, activate "Fusion Gate" to Fusion Summon Starving by using Barber + Jester as materials.

5) Copycat Nightingale with Starving to deal 8 x 500 = 4000 damage in total. Since the copycat ability of Starving isn't hard once-per turn, you can repeat it. To do so, return Barber + Jester to Extra Deck and hand with "Primal Seed". Then, Special Summon Jester with its ability to Link Summon Barber by using Starving + Jester as materials.

6) Special Summon Jester and return Starving to Extra Deck with "Primal Seed". Then, Fusion Summon Starving with Barber + Jester. In short, repeat these steps explained in #4 + #5, while copycatting Nightingale with Starving and pulling the trigger, until your opponent is dead.

So, in total, you can save up to 630 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

deck_excerpt: I've got a bone to pick with you
deck_description: Casual Skull Servant deck to one-shot your friends

After making the other 3 Visas decks, i wanted to give Tearlaments a shot; but i couldn't afford the Horus Cards. So instead of waiting to even buy them, i decided to brainstorm with a Lightsworn engine to see if Tearlaments can utilize it.

PROS:
- The Minerva Rank 4 gives access to extra mills (and draws if you hit a lightsworn), so you'll always have and extra monster on field to go into Cross-Sheep.

- Borreload Savage can be played since if you have Raiden on field and go into Spright Sprind to make Merrli, make Mudragon - then Synchro into Borreload Savage and target Cross-Sheep in grave.

- If you draw (or search) Raiden and find a way to make Garura or mill Malicious, you can always make a Baronne de Fleur. (Also Tearlament Kashtira + Minerva lvl 3 or Destrudo)

- Shaddoll Winda on opponents turn because of Kaleido-Heart and Sulliek (if you have a Shaddoll in grave of course)

- Wulf and Night Sword Serpent can be an extra body on board for Borreload Savage, Minerva Rank 4, Cross-Sheep, anything you need.

CONS:
- Charge of the Light Brigade sends for COST.. (errata pls konami)

- You can still chain-block with most cards that get sent to GY, but its still difficult to play if one card gets hit.

- More food for Bystials.


If you have any ideas for improvements for the deck, lmk
Have fun!

deck_excerpt: Ghostrick Angel of Mischief FTK ft. Epurrely Plump
deck_description:
Heya! Want to jumpscare your opponent with a mischievous cat? If you are, let me explain how...

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, send "Book of Moon" to Banish Zone (BZ). However you want to do is up to you.

2) Special Summon Kuriboh with Saryuja and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop.

3) Special Summon Level 1 dude with Panda. Then, edit their levels to 2 with "Falling Current" and XYZ Summon Plump by using them as materials.

4) With "Primal Seed" loop, fetch spells from BZ to your hand in a way that your GY should contain at least 7 spells in total when you play "Contract with the Void" except combo pieces. If you have more than 7, set "Primal Seed" + "Book of Taiyou" + "Scroll of Bewitchment" + "Astral Force" and play "Contract with the Void" to discard your hand to GY.

5) Feed your cat by attaching Spells/Traps from GYs. Remember, you can repeat this process by resetting Plump with Book spells and it shouldn't contain more than 9 materials. Thus, you need to attach 7 materials into Plump and nothing more.

6) When Plump has 9 materials, activate "Scroll of Bewitchment" to change its Attribute to DARK...

  • Come to think of it, "Lair of Darkness" does the same. You can check it in "Side Deck".

7) Finally, play "Astral Force" to overlay into Angel of Mischief and jumpscare your opponent to win the duel!

deck_excerpt: Librarian Mill FTK ft. Venom Bros + De-Synchro + Fusion Gate
deck_description:
Greetings! Once upon a time, I have done a FTK setup with Independent Nightingale, where every single variant of Venom Fusion monsters were used to burn your opponent to death. This time, Venom Bros are up to task to mill your opponent with Librarian. Let's go!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Plant all five flowers to opposing side with "Black Garden". Next, Link Summon Saryuja and place "Fusion Gate".

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Then, give Librarian to opposing side by getting rid of a flower and replacing with "Mystic Box".

3) With "Primal Seed" loop and probably Panda/Reborn, Fusion Summon all Venom Bros with "Fusion Gate" and activate their abilities to copycat Librarian. Then, replace flowers with them via "Mystic Box", similar to how you did in #2 for Librarian. Here is an example of Fusion Summon order and note that "H" is for in-hand and "F" is for field:

  1. Fusion Summon "Supreme King Dragon" by using Odd-Eyes (H) + Zero King (H) as materials. Don't copycat with "Supreme King Dragon" just yet.
  2. Fetch Odd-Eyes with "Primal Seed" and Fusion Summon "Odd-Eyes Venom Dragon" by using Supreme King (F) + Odd-Eyes (H) as materials. Copycat Librarian with Venom Dragon and pass it with "Mystic Box".
  3. Fetch Odd-Eyes + Zero King with "Primal Seed" and try Fusion Summoning "Supreme King Dragon" again. This time, you can copycat Librarian with Supreme King and pass it with "Mystic Box".
  4. Fusion Summon "Starving Venom" by using 2 x DARK (F) as materials. As long as you don't use Chaos Emperor as material by accident, you will be fine. Just like the others, copycat Librarian with Starving Venom and pass it with "Mystic Box".
  5. Fetch Zero King with "Primal Seed" and Fusion Summon "Starving Venemy" by using DARK (H or F) + Zero King (H) as materials. Similar to previous setup, don't use Chaos Emperor as material by accident. Copycat Librarian with Venemy and replace Librarian with Venemy by destroying Librarian with "Mystic Box".

4) If you have done everything correct so far, there should be 4 x Venom monsters disguised as "T.G. Hyper Librarian", ready to mill your opponent. Refill the last spot by reviving Librarian with "Monster Reborn" and destroying the flower with "Mystic Box".

5) Fetch Zero King with "Primal Seed" and Special Summon Zero King with Saryuja. Tribute any two monsters but Chaos Emperor with Zero King to shut down anything your opponent can activate from Hand + GY + Backrow in the future.

6) Choose a monster you are going to Synchro Summon over and over again with "De-Synchro". I picked Ancient by using Panda + Martial as materials but any Synchro will do. Arrange your monsters accordingly with Panda and Reborn, if you must.

7) Each time you Synchro Summon, your opponent is going to draw 5 cards. Repeat what was explained in #6 until your opponent is out of cards.

deck_excerpt: Volcannon FTK ft. Black Garden + Fusion Gate + Land Flipping
deck_description:
Welcome! This is a basic deck, where the aim is to burn your opponent with Volcannon by targeting Jizukiru forever. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Activate "Black Garden" and "Fusion Gate". To make sure either are present on the field, pass one of them to your opponent with "Land Flipping".

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Then, replace a flower with Jizukiru. In return, "Black Garden" is going to plant a flower to your side, just like how you refilled your opponent's side by Summoning monsters on your side.

3) When you have Inari in your hand, activate "Clockwork Night" to change everything as Type into Machine. Next, activate "Fusion Gate", wherever it is, by banishing Inari from your hand and any monster but Chaos Emperor from your field as materials to Fusion Summon Volcannon.

4) Target Jizukiru with Volcannon to deal original ATK of Jizukiru as damage to your opponent, which is 3300. Volcannon doesn't look at ATK modifications done on the field. Instead, Volcannon checks the ATK of monster in GY, that's why the damage output was higher than it would seem.

5) With Jizukiru + Volcannon being destroyed, banish them with "Soul Release". Then, fetch Jizukiru + Inari to your hand with "Primal Seed" and return Volcannon to Extra Deck with "Primal Seed".

6) To make it a loop, repeat these steps from 2 to 5, until your opponent is dead. Since you will always get a flower by placing Jizukiru to your opponent's side thanks to "Black Garden", you can always Fusion Summon Volcannon without any issues.

deck_name: MASTER DUEL - YOU CAN BUILD THIS DECK WITH STRUCTURE DECK BLUE-EYES MAX - NEW UPDATE ANNIVERSARY.
deck_description: Master Duel have announced the first details of an upcoming Selection Pack, Ride Into The Future, as well as the Blue-Eyes MAX Structure Deck, releasing on February 7th as part of Master Duel's 2nd Anniversary. Today I will give you an interesting idea for using STRUCTURE DECK BLUE-EYES MAX. Below is the deck profile of the deck for everyone to refer to.
prog

The gameplan is simple with this deck. Try to summon Junk Speeder as soon as possible, and summon Satellite, Jet, and Junk Synchron from the deck, if you have to summon Quickdraw along side, just try to keep Road Synchron in your deck as much as possible. If you used Dopplewarrior for the synchro summon, activate his effect after Junk Speeder to get the two tokens. After that you can go into Crystal Wing if you cannot extend, or the appropriate synchro for the situation. They are a few ways you can summon Shooting Quasar on your first turn, however you can only get it with Junk Speeder(5), Scarred Warrior(5), Stardust Charge(6), Accel Synchro(tuner and adjustable levels wanting either 1, or 2) or Synchro Formula(2). If you can get Speeder/Scarred out with Stardust Charge, and Accel Synchro, you will want to send Road Synchron to the grave to reduce the level by 4. If you have Speeder, and Scarred, you can use either Formula, or Accel Synchro by sending Junk Synchron to the grave. Either way, you will be able to get other monsters out if you cannot go for Quasar.
